Not sure if this is the proper platform to ask questions about ant&#39;s JUnit
task, but in lack of a better one, here goes:

What I want to do is cause the build to fail if any JUnit tests fail.
However, even if one test fails, I want to continue running all the other
tests, so that one test does not hide an error from another one.  My problem
is that I cannot get JUnit both to cause a failure of the build AND run all
test.  It&#39;s always just one or the other.  The junit task is defined like
this:

&lt;junit fork=&quot;yes&quot; haltonfailure=&quot;on&quot; printsummary=&quot;on&quot;&gt;
	&lt;batchtest fork=&quot;yes&quot; haltonfailure=&quot;on&quot; todir=&quot;./tests&quot;&gt;
		&lt;fileset dir=&quot;${class.java.test.dir}&quot;&gt;
			&lt;include name=&quot;**/*Test*.class&quot; /&gt;
			&lt;exclude name=&quot;**/AllTests.class&quot; /&gt;
		&lt;/fileset&gt;
	&lt;/batchtest&gt;
	&lt;formatter type=&quot;plain&quot; /&gt;
	&lt;classpath refid=&quot;test.classpath&quot;/&gt;
&lt;/junit&gt;

1 - Why are there two haltonfailure attributes?

2 - Is it possible to set them (or any others) so that I get the desired
behaviour?
